[[File:The American Museum journal (c1900-(1918)) (18160239765).jpg|thumb|Matausch at work in 1915]]
'''Ignaz Matausch''' (September 1, 1859 – December 14, 1915) was an Austrian-American artist and [[entomology|entomologist]] known for his models of insects and other invertebrates at the [[American Museum of Natural History]]. Born in [[Budweis]], he emigrated to the United States in 1892 and resided in [[Cleveland, Ohio]], until 1904, when he became a member of the modeling staff of the American Museum. He was known for his realistic large-scale models including the flea, house fly, and spider. As an entomologist he focused on [[treehopper]]s (Membracidae), authoring eight papers on their biology.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Ignaz Matausch|first=Roy W.|last=Miner|journal=Journal of the New York Entomological Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WHMVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA155|year=1916|pages=155–157|volume=24}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=A Huge Model of the Flea|journal=Scientific American|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=isoxAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA260-IA3|year=1914|page=260}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Current Notes|journal=Journal of Economic Entomology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQn0AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA515|year=1916|volume=9|page=515}}</ref>

